        "update_time": null,
        "content": {
          "content_type": "text",
          "parts": [
            "Great question. Here’s how **Canvas** works with me:\n\n### What Canvas Is\n- When we create a **Canvas**, it’s like opening a side-by-side document editor next to our chat.\n- Instead of me just sending a single block of text here in chat, I can put the draft into Canvas so we can iterate on it together.\n- It’s especially useful for **longer pieces**—documents, essays, code files, structured notes, etc.\n\n### Commenting\n- You **can add comments directly in the Canvas** (like margin notes).\n- Each comment attaches to a specific section of the document.\n- I’ll see those comments and can reply **inline to the document** or in our chat thread, depending on what’s most natural.\n- If you want, I can also make edits in response to your comments—either just in the spot you called out, or across the whole doc.\n\n### Inline Responses\n- Unlike email where we’d nest quoted text and replies, in Canvas the workflow is closer to **Google Docs comments**: you leave a note on a section, I respond to that note, and we can resolve it once it’s addressed.\n- If you prefer an **email-style inline workflow**, you can also just paste comments into the doc itself, and I’ll reply in-line when I update it.\n\n---\n\n👉 Do you want me to spin up a quick **demo Canvas** for you, with a sample text, so you can try adding comments and see how I’d respond?"
          ]
        },
